{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487508"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:12:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:12:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"362"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/362"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.02,0.07,0.15,0.73]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"362"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96554"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/362"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"362"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79188"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"329"},{"type":"tags","id":"1156"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9450"},{"type":"tags","id":"9755"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"671"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1235"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32961"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44456"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44920"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96554"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of painful swelling under his left jaw. He reports jaw pain shortly after meals with the swelling becoming more noticeable approximately 30 minutes after eating. He has lost 2-3 kg of weight due to the pain and difficulty eating. His medical history includes gastric cancer (T1a N0 M0) for which he underwent successful partial gastrectomy 12 months ago. He does not take any regular medications. He denies fever, night sweats or chills.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. There is a visible 3 cm swelling in the left submandibular region (image). The swelling is mildly tender on palpation. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thyroglossal duct cyst","Epidermoid cyst","Branchial cleft cyst","Metastatic deposit in a lymph node","Submandibular duct calculus"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic features of sialolithiasis - a stone within the salivary gland or duct system. The key diagnostic features are the painful submandibular swelling that worsens after meals when salivary flow increases. This pattern strongly suggests an obstructive process in the salivary duct system.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubmandibular duct calculus\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis. The submandibular gland is the most common site for salivary stones (80-90% of cases), due to several anatomical and physiological factors: the submandibular duct (Wharton\u0027s duct) is longer and more tortuous than other salivary ducts; the flow is against gravity; and submandibular saliva is more alkaline with higher mucin and calcium content. When a stone forms, it obstructs salivary flow, particularly during eating when salivation increases. This leads to painful distension of the gland, exactly as described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroglossal duct cyst\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a midline neck mass that moves upward with tongue protrusion. It is a congenital anomaly that usually presents in childhood or young adulthood. The lateral location and relationship to eating make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpidermoid cyst\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign, slow-growing cyst containing keratin and lined with stratified squamous epithelium. These cysts do not typically change in size with eating and would not cause the meal-related symptoms described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranchial cleft cyst\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a painless lateral neck mass anterior to the sternocleidomastoid muscle. These congenital anomalies usually become apparent in the second or third decade of life and do not have the characteristic relationship with eating seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetastatic deposit in a lymph node\u003C/strong\u003E is an important consideration given the patient\u0027s history of gastric cancer. However, several features make this less likely: the early stage of his original cancer (T1a N0 M0) suggests a low risk of recurrence; metastatic deposits typically do not fluctuate in size with eating; and gastric cancer metastases to cervical lymph nodes would more commonly affect supraclavicular nodes (Virchow\u0027s node) rather than submandibular nodes.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003EManagement of submandibular duct calculi includes hydration, sialogogues (substances that stimulate salivary flow), analgesics, and potentially antibiotics if infection is present. Definitive treatment may involve stone removal via minimally invasive techniques such as sialendoscopy, or surgical approaches depending on the size and location of the stone.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Submandibular duct calculi typically present with painful swelling that worsens during or after meals when salivary flow increases.","The submandibular gland is the most common site for salivary stones due to its tortuous duct, alkaline saliva, and high mucin and calcium content.","Post-prandial pain and swelling in the submandibular region is highly characteristic of salivary duct obstruction."],"references":["Wilson KF, Meier JD, Ward PD. Salivary gland disorders. Am Fam Physician 2014; 89:882. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2014/0601/p882.html","Alyas F, Lewis K, Williams M, et al. Diseases of the submandibular gland as demonstrated using high resolution ultrasound. Br J Radiol 2005; 78:362. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15774602/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79188"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"362"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18429"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18429"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9d047b89-e621-4e10-b115-803577ccff45.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9d047b89-e621-4e10-b115-803577ccff45.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79188"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T08:46:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T08:48:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"362"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96554"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"pos